			<div class="editsection" style="float:right;margin-left:5px;">[<a href="/wiki?title=Phase_1&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Phase 1: License Porting">edit</a>]</div><a name="Phase_1:_License_Porting"></a><h2> Phase 1: License Porting </h2>
<p>1.1 Creative Commons identifies the Legal Project Lead and the Affiliate Institution for license porting.  Our decision to begin drafting a license for a particular country depends entirely on identifying a Legal Project Lead and an affiliate institution/law firm for that country.  Selection criteria for these practitioners and academics include:
</p>
<ul><li> Professional legal credentials and reputation, generally;
</li><li> Reputation among copyright and intellectual property experts;
</li><li> Enthusiasm for the project;
</li><li> Willingness to work within the framework described in these Guidelines;
</li><li> Ability to communicate in English; and
</li><li> Willingness to establish contacts and to collaborate with experts in the technology field.
</li></ul>
<p>The Legal Project Lead will head up the particular country’s drafting effort for licenses. These people will be in charge of soliciting and filtering comments from their community of lawyers and ultimately drafting the final changes. It is best to have this responsibility centralized, even if the peer review process is diffuse.
</p><p>More on <a href="/wiki/Choosing_a_Host_Institution" title="Choosing a Host Institution">Choosing a Host Institution</a>
</p><p>1.2 Creative Commons and Legal Project Lead/Affiliate Institution sign Memorandum of Understanding.  While we may in some cases facilitate informal discussion about a country’s participation in CCi before a Legal Project Lead is identified, we will not announce or draw attention to such discussions as “active” CCi countries until Creative Commons determines who this Legal Project Lead will be and the two parties sign a Memorandum of Understanding.
</p><p><br />
</p><p>1.3 Creative Commons registers the country domain name.
</p><p>1.4 Legal Project Lead establishes timeline of activities with CCi Director.  At the outset, the Legal Project Lead is to set out expected dates for completing steps in the Phase I license porting process. (Suggested timeframes are included with the steps that follow.) During the drafting process, serious problems should be called to the attention of the CCi Director when they become apparent.
</p><p>More on <a href="/wiki/Establishing_the_Timeline_of_Activities_for_Porting_the_Licenses" title="Establishing the Timeline of Activities for Porting the Licenses">Establishing the Timeline of Activities for Porting the Licenses</a>
</p><p>1.5 Legal Project Lead forms a Legal Advisory Board (optional).
</p><p>More on <a href="/wiki/Forming_a_Legal_Advisory_Board" title="Forming a Legal Advisory Board">Forming a Legal Advisory Board</a>
</p><p>1.6 Legal Project Lead produces first draft (suggested timeframe = one month). With the MOU signed, Creative Commons hands the controls over to the Legal Project Lead, who is to begin by producing a first draft of the new license.  Here’s how that drafting process should work:
</p><p>(a) Review the license.  The license you’ll be working from is the
newest version of Attribution-Noncommercial-ShareAlike license, found here <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/legalcode" class='external free' title="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/legalcode" rel="nofollow">http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/legalcode</a>.
</p><p>You should use this license as a basis for your draft because it is the most comprehensive Creative Commons license:  every provision that you will need to transpose for the 6 generic licenses appears in this license.
</p><p>(b) Translate the license (if applicable). Literally translate the license verbatim into your country’s first language.
</p><p>(c) Analyze and alter the license.  With the basic license literally translated into your country’s first language, it is time for you to begin the real challenge:  analysis of the license for provisions that must be changed in order to comport with your country’s laws, and revision of those provisions. Note that the original license is drafted to comport with U.S. law, whereas copyright law might be quite different in your country. (For example, your jurisdiction may provide for neighboring rights and moral rights and differ from the United States on “fair use”.) Also, you may want to add provisions on governing law and governing language clauses, and look at other, more conceptual issues.
</p><p>(d) Translate the changed license back to English and send it to the CCi Director.  This step is tedious, yes, but it helps us keep up with your changes and progress. (We apologize for the fact that we are not as multilingual as you. Thank you for being patient with us on this point – it demonstrates why your help is crucial to Creative Commons International's success!)
</p><p>1.7 Draft is released for Public Discussion (suggested timeframe = one month). With the first draft and English translation ready for comment, Creative Commons announces the addition of a new CCi country and establishes an email list for public feedback on the license drafts.   The Legal Project Lead, with guidance from the CCi Director, encourages comment and criticism. The language in which this discussion takes place as a rule will be the language of the jurisdiction concerned.
</p><p>More on <a href="/wiki/Conducting_the_Public_Discussion" title="Conducting the Public Discussion">Conducting the Public Discussion</a>
</p><p>1.8 Legal Project Lead produces Second Draft (suggested timeframe = two weeks). The Legal Project Lead revises the first draft in response to the discussion group’s suggestions. The re-draft should incorporate necessary changes to the licenses themselves and to their explanations (e.g., FAQs, disclaimers, human-readable “Commons Deeds”). Here again, we would ask that you please provide an English translation of this second draft.
</p><p>More on <a href="/wiki/Writing_an_explanation_of_any_changes_made_to_the_generic_license_during_the_porting_process" title="Writing an explanation of any changes made to the generic license during the porting process">Writing an explanation of any changes made to the generic license during the porting process</a> and <a href="/wiki/Producing_the_Second_Draft_of_the_License" title="Producing the Second Draft of the License">Producing the Second Draft of the License</a>
</p><p>1.9 Creative Commons reviews Second Draft (suggested timeframe = one month). In some cases, we might do this “review” on the public email list; in others, offline.  Either way, the CCi Director will work with the Legal Project Lead to produce a suitable final version.  In some cases, this process may be intense, given the amount of translation that may need to occur during the revision process.
</p><p>More on <a href="/wiki?title=Reviewing_the_Second_Draft_with_the_CCi_Director&amp;action=edit" class="new" title="Reviewing the Second Draft with the CCi Director">Reviewing the Second Draft with the CCi Director</a>
</p><p>1.10 Legal Project Lead sees to it that final licenses are re-translated into English.
</p><p><br />
</p>
<div class="editsection" style="float:right;margin-left:5px;">[<a href="/wiki?title=Phase_1&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Technical Requirements">edit</a>]</div><a name="Technical_Requirements"></a><h1> Technical Requirements </h1>
<p>1.11 TRANSLATION OF THE CHOOSE LICENCE WEBSITE
</p>
<pre>(ATTENTION: THIS WILL TAKE MUCH LONGER THAN YOU WOULD EXPECT!)
</pre>
<p>Legal Project Lead arranges the necessary translation and customization of the Commons Deed, the FAQs and other Web site content for the launch (suggested timeframe = one to two months). While finalizing and translating the final version of the licenses (and mapping the Attribution-Noncommercial-ShareAlike license into six different licenses), the Legal Project Lead conducts the translation and customization of the Commons Deeds and other necessary Web content (e.g., trademark and other policies, “choose license” at  <a href="http://a2.creativecommons.org:9000/istr" class='external free' title="http://a2.creativecommons.org:9000/istr" rel="nofollow">http://a2.creativecommons.org:9000/istr</a>, etc.)  If necessary, the Legal Project Lead will translate the FAQ of Creative Commons and add country specific FAQs to guide people’s proper use of the licenses.
</p><p><b>Translation of strings required for “choose license” and deeds at <a href="http://a2.creativecommons.org:9000/istr" class='external free' title="http://a2.creativecommons.org:9000/istr" rel="nofollow">http://a2.creativecommons.org:9000/istr</a> should proceed weeks if not months prior to expected launch.</b>
</p><p>This stage will include cooperative work with the technological staff of Creative Commons to prepare the license engine page.  The Legal Project Lead may wish to prepare Web contents for public relations purposes as well (working with the Public Project Lead if one has been designated).
</p><p>All ported licenses <b>must</b> be provided to Creative Commons as UTF8-encoded XHTML.  The XHTML <b>must</b> be modeled after the XHTML used in other Creative Commons licenses, including using the same stylesheet.  The XHTML provided <b>must</b> be <a href="http://validator.w3.org/" class='external text' title="http://validator.w3.org/" rel="nofollow">valid</a> according to the <a href="http://validator.w3.org/" class='external text' title="http://validator.w3.org/" rel="nofollow">W3C Markup Validator</a>.  Do <b>not</b> attempt to generate license HTML form Microsoft Word.  It produces junk HTML, which will be returned to you and you'll have to redo.
</p><p>License files <b>must</b> be named according to the following convention:
</p>
<pre>{license-code}_{version}_{country-code}.html
</pre>
<p>In other words, Austria would provide the following six files:
</p>
<pre>by-nc-nd_2.5_at.html
by-nc-sa_2.5_at.html
by-nc_2.5_at.html
by-nd_2.5_at.html
by-sa_2.5_at.html
by_2.5_at.html
</pre>
<p>Please validate using the W3C service above before sending to Creative Commons tech staff.  <b>REPEAT: YOU MUST VALIDATE USING THE W3C VALIDATOR BEFORE SENDING TO CC STAFF.  IF YOU DO NOT THE HTML WILL NOT BE ACCEPTED UNTIL YOU DO.</b>
</p><p>!PLEASE NOTE THAT NO FURTHER CHANGES WILL BE POSSIBLE ONCE THEY HAVE BEEN PUBLISHED!
</p><p>1.12 Ported licenses are posted on creativecommons.org.  Creative Commons places the full final licenses as well as the Commons Deeds on its Web site in the national language of this new participant country.
</p><p>1.13 The Launch is celebrated. Whether the Launch be in the form of a party, a convention, a television program, a press conference, or all of the above will be the decision of the Legal Project Lead and the Community Project Lead (if this position has been filled). The event should attract the kind of publicity we need to make sure that people will know where to turn for “creative work available for others to create upon and share.”
</p><p>Further information on Phase I License Porting is presented in the Creative Commons <a href="/wiki/DVD" title="DVD">DVD</a>.
</p><p>1.14 Legal Project Lead and CCi Director discuss if the Affiliate Institution is interested to become a longterm Legal Advisor for the particular jurisdiction. If this should not be the case the Projet Lead suggests other potential Affiliate Institutions for this position.
</p>
